03:09.754 --> 03:12.625
<i>It is important
to understand about dying</i>

03:12.657 --> 03:14.459
<i>that even though in general</i>

03:14.492 --> 03:17.263
<i>you do not have a personal
choice in the matter,</i>

03:17.295 --> 03:19.564
<i>it is going to happen to you
when it happens to you.</i>

03:19.598 --> 03:21.434
<i>There are reasons you die.</i>

03:22.568 --> 03:24.370
<i>There are causes,</i>

03:24.402 --> 03:28.373
<i>a chain of events
linked by causality,</i>

03:28.407 --> 03:30.475
<i>and those events
include decisions</i>

03:30.508 --> 03:34.579
<i>that you have
personally made.</i>

03:34.612 --> 03:37.883
<i>How did you end up here,
on this exact day,</i>

03:37.915 --> 03:39.985
<i>at this exact time,</i>

03:40.019 --> 03:43.890
<i>with this specific event
happening to you?</i>

04:05.510 --> 04:06.545
Hey!

04:35.908 --> 04:38.544
<i>May our mourners rise.</i>

04:41.447 --> 04:44.750
<i>Today we mourn the loss
of young Jonah Greenberg,</i>

04:44.783 --> 04:47.753
fallen in Korea,
fighting for his country,

04:47.786 --> 04:49.622
at 19 years of age.

04:49.654 --> 04:51.690
<i>Moses Greenberg,</i>

04:51.723 --> 04:54.959
<i>please, to recite
the kaddish.</i>

04:57.463 --> 04:58.597
Amen.

05:08.673 --> 05:09.641
Amen.

05:29.595 --> 05:30.563
Mm-hmm?

05:33.165 --> 05:34.633
Yeah, sure.

05:34.665 --> 05:35.935
Ah.

05:35.968 --> 05:37.603
Hi, Mrs. Greenberg.

05:37.636 --> 05:39.105
I'm so sorry
for your loss.

05:39.137 --> 05:41.539
Ah, yes, Marcus.

05:41.572 --> 05:44.543
You're such
a clever boy.

05:44.576 --> 05:47.480
Jonah, he... he always
looked up to you.

05:47.512 --> 05:49.048
Maybe not
such close friends,

05:49.081 --> 05:51.917
but he respected...

05:51.949 --> 05:53.519
We were teammates.

05:53.552 --> 05:55.521
He was
a really good guy.

05:55.553 --> 05:57.489
Baseball.

05:57.523 --> 05:58.958
He enjoyed...

06:00.692 --> 06:01.793
Marcus...

06:01.826 --> 06:03.396
don't go into this war,

06:03.428 --> 06:05.798
<i>for your parents' sake.</i>

06:05.831 --> 06:08.033
<i>You should be
a baseball star.</i>

06:08.065 --> 06:09.901
<i>Don't go
into this draft.</i>

06:09.935 --> 06:12.670
He's going
to college, Miriam.

06:12.704 --> 06:15.375
They keep the ones in college
from the draft.

06:16.475 --> 06:19.677
Such a clever boy,
Marcus.

06:19.711 --> 06:21.847
A scholarship,
is that right?

06:21.879 --> 06:24.850
Yes. In Ohio,
this college is.

06:24.882 --> 06:26.952
Ohio?

06:29.187 --> 06:31.089
How will you
keep kosher?

06:37.095 --> 06:40.666
<i>Only one thing worse than dying
by getting stabbed with a bayonet,</i>

06:40.699 --> 06:41.669
and that's dying by

06:41.670 --> 06:43.670
getting stabbed with a
bayonet when you're still a virgin.

06:43.701 --> 06:45.937
And Greenberg was
definitely a virgin.

06:45.971 --> 06:48.607
Oh, yeah? I thought maybe
you and Greenberg

06:48.639 --> 06:50.575
had taken care of each other
before he shipped out.

06:50.608 --> 06:52.144
Shut up, asshole.

06:52.177 --> 06:54.680
So, uh...

06:54.713 --> 06:57.082
when do you report?

06:58.115 --> 06:59.718
Two weeks.

07:01.052 --> 07:03.755
Ah, you'll be okay.

07:03.788 --> 07:05.957
You're smarter
than Greenberg.

07:05.990 --> 07:07.860
Not as smart as you.

07:29.615 --> 07:32.084
Mrs. Davidovich.
Two chickens?

07:32.117 --> 07:33.686
Let me see.

07:33.718 --> 07:35.153
Of course. Markie!

07:35.187 --> 07:37.723
<i>Flick two chickens for
Mrs. Davidovich, will ya?</i>

07:40.892 --> 07:41.893
Turn 'em around.

07:44.228 --> 07:45.630
Yeah.

07:45.663 --> 07:48.800
I'll wrap them for you.

07:48.834 --> 07:52.103
So what will you do when
this one goes off next month?

07:52.137 --> 07:54.807
The Mrs. will help,
like the old days.

07:54.839 --> 07:57.943
<i>I can't keep him here
chopping meat like me.</i>

08:13.057 --> 08:15.260
I have to go
see Gurevich.

08:15.293 --> 08:17.996
You can
close up early.

08:18.029 --> 08:20.899
Oh, and bring home some brisket
for your mother.

08:22.300 --> 08:23.735
I told you, Dad,

08:23.769 --> 08:26.739
I'm going out with Davey
and Sam tonight.

08:26.771 --> 08:27.939
You didn't tell me.

08:27.973 --> 08:29.108
Mm-hmm. I told you,

08:29.141 --> 08:30.709
we're going
to the pictures.

08:30.742 --> 08:32.945
To the pictures.

08:32.977 --> 08:35.046
I know what
you boys are doing.

08:35.080 --> 08:36.649
I heard
from Mrs. Pearlgreen

08:36.682 --> 08:39.552
about that Eddie
going to pool halls.

08:39.585 --> 08:41.787
Dad, I'm going
to the pictures.

08:41.820 --> 08:43.222
I, I told you.

08:43.254 --> 08:45.090
I'm... I'm not
Eddie Pearlgreen, for Christ's sake.

08:45.123 --> 08:46.859
I don't even know
how to play pool.

08:46.892 --> 08:48.260
He took
his father's car,

08:48.293 --> 08:49.995
drove all the way
to Scranton,

08:50.028 --> 08:52.664
to some special pool hall
they have there.

08:52.697 --> 08:55.000
He bets. He gambles.

08:55.033 --> 08:57.269
His father says he'll be
stealing cars next.

08:57.302 --> 08:59.337
W... What does Eddie Pearlgreen
have to do with me?

08:59.370 --> 09:02.707
Dad, I'm... I'm leaving
in less than a month.

09:02.740 --> 09:04.309
You think I'm tempted
to steal cars?

09:58.296 --> 09:59.765
Markie?

10:01.066 --> 10:02.601
Ma?

10:04.001 --> 10:06.904
Everything okay?
What's going on?

10:06.937 --> 10:08.874
Your father.

10:08.907 --> 10:10.309
What happened?

10:10.341 --> 10:13.111
He went out
looking for you.

10:13.144 --> 10:15.346
<i>He was worried.</i>

10:15.379 --> 10:17.081
He's been talking
to Artie Pearlgreen again.

10:17.115 --> 10:18.850
It got him all riled up.

10:18.884 --> 10:20.853
I think he smoked three packs
of cigarettes. Then he went.

10:20.885 --> 10:23.322
What's happening
to him, Ma?

10:23.355 --> 10:26.125
What's the matter
with him? He's crazy.

10:26.158 --> 10:28.159
He's driving me crazy.
He's driving you crazy.

10:28.192 --> 10:29.360
<i>It's your leaving.</i>

10:29.394 --> 10:30.962
It's all the boys dying,

10:30.995 --> 10:32.364
Bennie and Abe
in the last war,

10:32.397 --> 10:33.966
now this new war.
I don't know.

10:33.999 --> 10:36.034
He's worried about you.
He's worried about Ohio.

10:44.208 --> 10:46.310
So, there you are.

10:46.344 --> 10:49.381
Yeah, strange.
Here I am in my own house.

10:49.413 --> 10:51.182
I have been everywhere
looking for you.

10:51.216 --> 10:53.018
Oh, why? Why? Why?

10:53.051 --> 10:54.453
Somebody, tell me why.

10:54.485 --> 10:56.288
<i>Because if anything
were to happen to you...</i>

10:56.321 --> 10:57.723
Oh, come on.

10:57.755 --> 10:59.824
If anything were
to ever happen to you...

10:59.857 --> 11:02.126
What is this all about?

11:02.159 --> 11:04.462
It's about life, Markie.

11:04.495 --> 11:06.164
It's about
the tiniest mistake

11:06.197 --> 11:07.466
that can
have consequences.

11:07.499 --> 11:09.768
Oh, Christ. You sound
like a fortune cookie.

11:09.801 --> 11:11.870
Do I?
Like a fortune cookie?

11:11.903 --> 11:14.072
<i>Not like
the concerned father that I am,</i>

11:14.105 --> 11:15.474
<i>but like
a fortune cookie?</i>

11:15.506 --> 11:18.076
I can't take this anymore.
I can't take this.

11:18.110 --> 11:19.745
You know what?
Thank God I'm leaving.

11:19.778 --> 11:22.346
Thank God,
so I don't end up...

11:22.379 --> 11:25.283
What? End up what?

11:25.317 --> 11:28.453
I don't know.
I don't know.

11:58.015 --> 11:59.851
Maybe I shouldn't go.

12:02.187 --> 12:04.255
No.

12:04.288 --> 12:05.457
Come on.

12:08.159 --> 12:09.461
You go.

12:15.366 --> 12:18.203
You gotta stop worrying.
It's scaring Ma.

12:23.207 --> 12:24.809
You go.

12:25.876 --> 12:28.479
Just...

12:28.513 --> 12:30.182
be careful.

13:10.322 --> 13:11.889
<i>Everything's in the envelope.</i>

13:11.923 --> 13:13.558
You're in Jenkins 211.

13:13.591 --> 13:15.860
That's behind the men's quad,
back towards the gym.

13:15.894 --> 13:18.864
Keys are in there, and check
your class schedule in there, too.

13:18.897 --> 13:20.566
And looks like you're
doing a campus job.

13:20.599 --> 13:22.367
The job board's
right over there.

13:22.399 --> 13:24.903
Just take a ticket down from
the board for the job you want,

13:24.936 --> 13:26.437
and turn it back in
with the form.

13:26.471 --> 13:29.408
I'd go now. Otherwise,
all that's left is the dining hall.

13:59.403 --> 14:00.972
Hi. Marcus Messner.

14:01.005 --> 14:03.107
Hey. Ron Foxman.

14:03.140 --> 14:05.610
That's Bert Flusser.

14:05.644 --> 14:07.245
Where you from?

14:07.278 --> 14:08.647
- Newark.
- Where's that?

14:08.679 --> 14:11.250
- New Jersey.
- Right.

14:11.283 --> 14:12.651
Cleveland, Ohio.

14:12.683 --> 14:14.385
Flusser's
from Chicago.

14:14.418 --> 14:15.987
<i>He's, uh...</i>

14:16.020 --> 14:18.356
cultured.

14:18.389 --> 14:19.957
You'll see.

14:19.990 --> 14:22.360
Oh yeah?
Does Flusser talk?

14:22.394 --> 14:24.196
Oh, I talk all right.

14:24.229 --> 14:25.597
I even talk
in my sleep.

14:25.629 --> 14:27.432
I have so much to say,

14:27.465 --> 14:29.368
so much to share
with the world.

14:31.970 --> 14:34.206
Young freshman
Marcus Messner

14:34.239 --> 14:36.074
from Newark,
New Jersey.

14:36.106 --> 14:39.677
What a surprise to find yourself
in a triple with two other Jews.

14:39.711 --> 14:41.446
What a coincidence.

14:41.479 --> 14:44.149
Ronald and I are the only two Jews
at Winesburg

14:44.182 --> 14:45.951
<i>who are not
in the Jewish fraternity.</i>

14:45.984 --> 14:48.353
After all,
we are juniors.

14:48.385 --> 14:51.355
We ought to be living in style
over at Zeta Tau Mu,

14:51.389 --> 14:54.058
not bunking
with young freshman,

14:54.091 --> 14:56.028
Marcus Messner.

14:57.461 --> 14:59.697
# All of us with one heart #

14:59.730 --> 15:02.134
# With the torch
of freedom #

15:02.167 --> 15:04.670
<i># March on, march on #</i>

15:04.702 --> 15:08.406
# March on and on #

15:08.440 --> 15:12.411
# Cheelai, Cheelai,
Cheelai... #

15:12.443 --> 15:15.112
Bert, close the door
at least.

15:18.216 --> 15:20.318
Ronald doesn't
like Negro Communists,

15:20.351 --> 15:21.653
Paul Robeson
in particular.

15:21.686 --> 15:23.989
He doesn't like music
at all, in fact.

15:24.022 --> 15:26.158
If Dean Caudwell ever heard you
playing that commie propaganda,

15:26.191 --> 15:27.591
he'd probably toss you
right out of here.

15:27.625 --> 15:29.061
Dean Caudwell loves me.

15:29.094 --> 15:30.462
Dean Caudwell?

15:30.495 --> 15:32.063
<i>Bert:
Dean of Men.</i>

15:32.096 --> 15:36.300
And a man among deans,
if I do say so myself.

15:36.333 --> 15:39.303
In fact,
he's addressing us

15:39.336 --> 15:40.672
in 15 minutes.

15:40.705 --> 15:43.475
Oh, shit. Chapel.

15:43.508 --> 15:45.076
Uh...

15:45.110 --> 15:46.211
Chapel?

15:46.244 --> 15:48.312
Yeah. Didn't you
read the handbook?

15:48.346 --> 15:50.282
Required.
Every Wednesday at 11:00.

15:50.315 --> 15:51.984
You have to go to at least 10
of them a year

15:52.017 --> 15:53.185
if you want to graduate.

15:53.217 --> 15:55.453
Might as well
get started today.

15:58.023 --> 16:01.426
To you who join us today
for the first time,

16:01.458 --> 16:05.429
to you who enter
your final year

16:05.462 --> 16:09.201
looking out at the prospect
of what may seem to be

16:09.234 --> 16:12.137
an uncertain
and dangerous horizon,

16:12.169 --> 16:14.705
menaced as this country
may be

16:14.739 --> 16:18.509
by enemies
both foreign and native,

16:18.543 --> 16:20.379
fear not,

16:20.412 --> 16:23.248
puzzle not,

16:23.280 --> 16:26.017
hesitate not,

16:26.051 --> 16:28.620
for the spirit of Winesburg

16:28.653 --> 16:33.425
will animate
and fortify you.

16:33.457 --> 16:37.629
And now, Dr. Donehower
will lead us in prayer.

16:45.537 --> 16:49.708
<i>Righteous God,
who rules the nations,</i>

16:49.740 --> 16:53.711
<i>we pray that you guard all
the strong young men and women</i>

16:53.745 --> 16:56.480
<i>who enter the gates
of Winesburg College</i>

16:56.514 --> 17:00.752
<i>in the service of greater
knowledge and greater strength.</i>

17:00.784 --> 17:03.355
<i>To our fellow Winesburgians
currently serving</i>

17:03.388 --> 17:05.323
<i>the cause of freedom
in Korea...</i>

17:37.689 --> 17:40.159
<i>Order, arms.</i>

17:42.826 --> 17:44.730
Left shoulder, arms.

17:47.765 --> 17:49.802
Order, arms.

17:55.640 --> 17:56.708
Yes?

17:56.740 --> 17:58.309
<i>Call from
Marcus Messner.</i>

17:58.343 --> 17:59.711
Yes, I'll accept
the charges.

17:59.743 --> 18:01.645
Marcus? Marcus, honey?

18:01.679 --> 18:03.215
Yes, Mom. I'm here.

18:03.248 --> 18:05.584
<i>You sound tired.
Are you tired?</i>

18:05.616 --> 18:07.519
No, I'm not too tired.
I'm just busy.

18:07.551 --> 18:09.320
Tell me
about your classes.

18:09.354 --> 18:10.889
Have you gotten
any grades yet?

18:10.922 --> 18:12.691
<i>It's only been
two weeks, Ma.</i>

18:12.723 --> 18:16.260
<i>I've got an American History
paper due tomorrow.</i>

18:16.294 --> 18:18.263
Hold on. Your father
wants to talk...

18:18.296 --> 18:20.798
So, Marcus, what else?
What else is going on?

18:20.832 --> 18:23.568
Studying. Studying and working
at the library.

18:23.601 --> 18:25.504
<i>What are you doing
to divert yourself?</i>

18:25.537 --> 18:27.538
Nothing, I don't
need diversions.

18:27.571 --> 18:29.140
I don't have
the time for them.

18:29.173 --> 18:31.542
Is there a girl
in the picture yet?

18:31.576 --> 18:33.144
<i>Not yet.</i>

18:33.178 --> 18:34.379
You be careful.

18:34.412 --> 18:35.547
<i>I will be.</i>

18:35.579 --> 18:36.780
You know
what I mean.

18:36.814 --> 18:38.316
Yep.

18:38.348 --> 18:39.817
<i>You don't want to get
into any trouble.</i>

18:39.851 --> 18:41.520
I won't, Dad. Stop.

18:41.553 --> 18:43.688
That Karpen boy,

18:43.721 --> 18:45.656
the army sent him home.

18:45.690 --> 18:47.359
They found out
he has flat feet.

18:47.392 --> 18:49.794
<i>Gershowitz gave him
a job at the grocery.</i>

18:49.826 --> 18:51.663
<i>First thing,
he's delivering the groceries</i>

18:51.695 --> 18:53.464
<i>and crashes the truck.</i>

18:53.498 --> 18:55.734
<i>His mother was
crying in the store for an hour,</i>

18:55.767 --> 18:57.635
<i>an hour...</i>

19:10.981 --> 19:12.550
You're
Marcus Messner, right?

19:12.584 --> 19:13.751
I'm Sonny,
Sonny Cottler.

19:13.785 --> 19:15.387
This is
Marty Ziegler.

19:15.420 --> 19:16.955
We're wondering
if you have a couple of minutes,

19:16.988 --> 19:18.757
maybe head over
to The Owl for a soda.

19:18.789 --> 19:20.357
What's this all about?

19:20.391 --> 19:21.625
We're with
Zeta Tau Mu,

19:21.659 --> 19:23.461
the Jewish fraternity
on campus.

19:23.493 --> 19:25.196
We'd love to talk
to you about rushing.

19:28.499 --> 19:31.202
Look, look, I'm sorry.

19:31.236 --> 19:33.538
I don't think I'm
gonna join a fraternity.

19:33.570 --> 19:36.307
Well,
you don't have to.

19:36.340 --> 19:38.876
Why don't you just come over to
the house for dinner some time?

19:38.910 --> 19:41.479
You can come tomorrow night.
It's roast beef night.

19:41.511 --> 19:43.581
You'll have a good meal,
you'll meet some of the brothers,

19:43.615 --> 19:45.217
and there's no obligation
to do anything else.

19:45.250 --> 19:47.818
No. I don't believe
in fraternities.

19:47.852 --> 19:48.987
Believe in them?

19:49.019 --> 19:50.654
What is there
to believe in?

19:50.688 --> 19:51.923
Couple of like-minded guys
get together

19:51.955 --> 19:53.390
for friendship
and camaraderie.

19:53.423 --> 19:54.792
We play sports together.

19:54.826 --> 19:56.760
We hold parties
and dances.

19:56.794 --> 19:58.363
We share our meals
together.

19:58.395 --> 20:00.397
Look, it can get
awfully lonely otherwise.

20:00.431 --> 20:02.000
You know that out
of 1,400 people on campus,

20:02.032 --> 20:03.601
less than 80 are Jewish?

20:03.634 --> 20:05.636
That's a pretty small
percentage.

20:05.670 --> 20:08.473
The only other fraternity that'll
have a Jew is the nonsectarian house,

20:08.506 --> 20:10.275
and they don't have
much going for them

20:10.307 --> 20:13.278
in the way of facilities
or really anything.

20:13.310 --> 20:15.346
I'm a senior, Marcus,
and president of the house.

20:15.380 --> 20:16.748
I don't want
to pressure you,

20:16.780 --> 20:18.349
but some of the brothers,
they've seen you around.

20:18.383 --> 20:19.651
They think you'd make
a great addition.

20:19.683 --> 20:21.752
They say you seem to be
a real scholar.

20:21.786 --> 20:24.489
Did you know that since Zeta Tau
was formed just 10 years ago,

20:24.521 --> 20:26.991
we've won the Interfraternity
Scholarship Cup five times,

20:27.025 --> 20:28.393
more than any other house?

20:28.425 --> 20:30.327
Sonny's being modest,
Marcus.

20:30.361 --> 20:32.530
He's actually the President of the
Interfraternity Council this year.

20:32.563 --> 20:33.965
Listen, that's great,

20:33.998 --> 20:35.700
and I appreciate
you coming around,

20:35.732 --> 20:38.269
but I'm not going to be
joining any fraternity.

20:38.303 --> 20:39.571
Can I ask why?

20:39.604 --> 20:42.407
I just...

20:42.440 --> 20:44.542
I have my job.
I have my studies.

20:44.575 --> 20:46.911
I'm just
not in the market

20:46.943 --> 20:49.681
for anything more
than that right now.

20:49.713 --> 20:51.282
Thank you, anyways.

20:51.316 --> 20:52.683
I hope you're
not offended.

20:52.717 --> 20:54.552
I'm not offended at all.

20:54.585 --> 20:56.554
I admire your
determination. Yeah.

20:56.586 --> 20:58.956
Give me a ring at the house if
you think about it some more

20:58.990 --> 21:00.759
or if you
need anything at all.

21:00.791 --> 21:04.461
And if you decide to stay for dinner,
all the better. Deal?

21:04.494 --> 21:06.664
Sure. Sure.

21:06.698 --> 21:08.367
All right.

21:11.702 --> 21:13.904
But the Puritans faced
a particular challenge,

21:13.938 --> 21:15.940
as, by the 1660s,

21:15.972 --> 21:17.741
the first generation
began to die out.

21:17.775 --> 21:20.512
<i>So in 1662,</i>

21:20.545 --> 21:22.681
the Reverend
Solomon Stoddard

21:22.713 --> 21:25.383
devised the so-called
Half-Way Covenant,

